The head of the White House and his wife Michelle will land in the morning in the Norwegian metropolis and will have a full schedule.
He will first go to the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the first time the five members of the Committee who selected him in October among 172 people and 33 organizations.
The planning of the presidential couple then provides an interview with the king of Norway Harald V and Queen Sonja.
The visit will meet its summit in the afternoon at a solemn ceremony where Obama will receive the prestigious reward.
He will be the fourth American president to receive it, but only the third one who will be awarded the prize in the Committee's very presence.
The White House informed in advance that Obama would talk about the war in Afghanistan at the award.
The President does not want to avoid this because he is aware that he receives this prize by being a President who leads a war in two countries at present.
He strengthened the war effort a few days ago by sending additional units to Afghanistan, which none of his critics would forget to highlight.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive a gold medal, a degree and a check of ten million Swedish crowns (about 1.1 million Euros).
He intends to donate to charitable works, but has not yet specifically decided which.
His programme will then take him and his wife to a banquet including, in addition to the king and queen of Norway, the head of government and 250 other guests.
Obama was rather reluctant at this price at the beginning.
He mentioned, for example, feeling that he did not deserve it fully.
He also repeated several times that it is not a price for himself, but for all those who defend the same values as him.
From the announcement, he stated that it would be an "invitation to act" for him.
