This reality, in some cases, takes the top on the fact that the combination does not deal as intensively with the current variants of the virus as well as some medicines already available.
It is not possible to cure AIDS at present.
However, the lives of patients can be radically extended through a combination of drugs that prevent the multiplication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, their consumption results in a series of side effects.
In addition, the repression of this multiplication has the effect of developing what is called resistant viruses on which drugs are no longer effective.
The work of the experts from three institutions, the Czech Republic Academy of Sciences, the Prague VŠCHT and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to coping with the resistance of the virus.
They have shown that substances called metal-carborates are acting on the protein responsible for multiplying the HIV virus.
Metalocarbons are an assembly of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination blocks the development of the virus in a different way from all the drugs used so far and that is why they could overcome the resistance problem.
The work of researchers leads them to discover new "improved" substances, based on their knowledge of the molecular mechanics of their links to virus proteins.
Metalocarbons have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-wall cages are formed by the atoms of boron, hydrogen and carbon and are connected by a metal atom, in this case the cobalt.
A betrayed and resistant virus.
HIV protease is a HIV virus protein that is essential to the life cycle of the virus.
Without the division of HIV virus caused by HIV protease, there would be no mature infectious particles in the virus.
If HIV protease is stopped, the spread of the virus in the patient's body will also be stopped, explaining researchers in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Cheque Science and Biochemistry of the Czech Republic Academy of Sciences.
In their work published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of combinations where two pairs of cages (see table) are linked by a short organic chain, which is then systematically modified.
A little weaker but more reliable.
