Management revolution or end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of large French companies, our fight for the development of economic intelligence will have been futile...
For more than a decade, the attitude of the management of large companies towards its employees has reminded the position of companies facing consumers before the marketing revolution: it is to make employees join "values" determined from above as it once was, to impose products designed by factory technicians to consumers.
By putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has given the strategies of conquest of markets in the place... although the authoritarian temptation to impose disconnected products from customer preference factors comes back regularly!
Demobilization of employees can result in deadly demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the emerging part of a much more general phenomenon that affects managers in particular.
This demobilization seriously undermines the development of all intellectual functions of the company, including R&D and, more importantly, economic intelligence.
Indeed, the EI "requires all stakeholders (...) a proactive approach and a prospective vision"; it requires employees to make a commitment that authoritarian management revenues are totally contrary to.
That is why we call for a management revolution that would be to place employees at the centre of the company's concerns as the client.
Any relative usefulness of internal opinion surveys
Internal opinion surveys – such as the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees – will they encourage this revolution in managerial practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
- First because I could see that, in the face of a new situation, all structures finally arrive, after many detours, to do priority... what she has always done.
- Then, because authoritarianism – one of the pathologies of power – increases proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behavior.
From the major engineering schools, they have a mechanical interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, by intellectual comfort, the old theory of life, recently reactivated by the "uniary neurosciences" and widely disseminated, to their unawareness, by the institutes of studies and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "leviers" (sic) of executive engagement, a recent survey of Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr comforts the leaders in a position of mechanical governance, inadequate to the world today.
Identifying and measuring mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises requires adopting a finalist vision of human behaviour.
It consists of integrating, in any reasoning or practice of governance, a fundamental finding: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it appears clearly as a means of achieving some of their dreams, ambitions, projects.
Currently, only the studies of the motivational analysis adopt this concept of employee motivations.
These studies have demonstrated that they judge their business based on a predetermined doxa that enables them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to carry out their life projects.
Through the identification and measurement of these mobilisation factors, business leaders can control, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and restore their management of human resources "to the place".
They thus create an area conducive to the concerted development of a robust and effective economic intelligence.
