75% of working mothers have had occupational problems due to their maternity
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women in younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is what the study "Women's fertility and career in Spain" carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Institute of Women.
The survey of 9,737 women between the ages of 15 and 75 did not leave any doubt: 75% of working mothers had a limited career because of maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences between the start of life in couples and the number of children, whether or not the woman works and the type of employment employed.
Those who have no activity outside the home, work part-time or have unstable work, get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, repel the entry into marriage and the first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women aged 35 to 49 years of fixed employment have their first child, on average 3.7 years after they settled in a couple. This figure goes to 4.1 among those working in the public sector. "This data shows that women with stable employment needed more time in their lives to get it, which led them to push back the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment exerted significantly affects maternity, but less the date of common beginning of life," says the researcher at CSIC Margarita Delgado.
The level of studies is another factor that widens the age gap of women's marriage and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they get married and have their first child late.
The difference is also maintained among women of the same generation.
For example, in the group between 35 and 49 years of age, those who did elementary and higher studies were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 years on average.
"Another distinction also appears among women, depending on their level of study.
While those who have completed elementary studies marry and have their first child before finding a stable job, those who have completed middle-level or higher-level studies reverse this program and give priority to obtaining stable work as a precondition for marriage and the arrival of a child," says Delgado.
